comment.author: 86818123@N00
comment._content:
This is certainly a spectacular image.  We're fortunate enough to have a 16"x12" archive copy of this from the original plate negative hanging on our wall (plus another of Ponting's photos of Scott's ship, the Terra Nova).  Believe me, the quality of the image is astounding.
What is also astounding is that Ponting could work in the polar conditions.  The photographs were taken on glass plate negatives as Ponting wanted the quality to be better than that obtained on photographic film (which had been around for about 20 years at the time).  A problem with this is that the plates were liable to crack if taken back inside too quickly for processing because of the temperature differential.

comment.author: 25453448@N02
comment._content: I've adored this picture ever since I was a kid. I have Herbert Ponting's book (Great White South) with a very similar picture in it (he evidently took several). This was of course on Scott's fatal expedition whose centenary is this year (1911), and the ship is the Terra Nova. We have the scientific collections from this expedition in our workplace (Natural History Museum, London). How fantastic that we can now see this great historical picture digitised on Flickr, and how fantastic that I just happened to chance on it in 'Explore'. Absolutely wonderful !!!
